                   </ul>\r\n		</li>    \r\n                <li><a href=\"<?php echo $GLOBALS[\"blogLink\"];?>/team\">About Us</a></li>\r\n                <li><a href=\"<?php echo $GLOBALS[\"blogLink\"];?>\">Blog</a></li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n        </div>\r\n<h1 class=\"betaTitle\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Beta</h1>\r\n<div class=\"betaTitleBar\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"jobsTitleText\">\r\n<p>Experienced entrepreneurs say that you fall in love with a problem first, then you innovate a solution. At FoundOPS, the problems we’ve fallen in love with are those facing small field service companies. Where are my technicians? What job am I going to next? Have all of my customers paid me? If you’ve ever managed a service team, you know how difficult these problems can be. Wouldn’t it be great if there was a system that helped you keep track of everything? It would be easy to setup and easier to use. You would be able log in through your computer and see exactly where your team was. Assigning jobs would be as simple as dragging and dropping. Technicians would see their next jobs on their mobile phones and be able to use turn-by-turn navigation to get their fast. And it would be cloud based so your data would be secure and you could access it from anywhere with an Internet connection. </p>\r\n<p>Sounds simple enough, right? So that’s what we’ve set out to do. It’s taken some time, a few pivots, but now we’re starting to see a pretty good system take face. However in order for it to become a great system, we know we need your help. Did we make the buttons on our mobile app big enough for you to use with your work gloves on? Is there some feature you just have to have? If shaping the next generation of service software sounds like something you might be interested in, complete the form below and we’ll get in contact with you.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<form action=\"http://foundops.us2.list-manage1.com/subscribe/post?u=6d3ef2a57e38d002d394a6527&amp;id=a6987117dc\" method=\"post\" id=\"mc-embedded-subscribe-form\" name=\"mc-embedded-subscribe-form\" class=\"validate\" target=\"_blank\">\r\n	                    <h2>Beta Program Signup</h2>\r\n                        <div class=\"field\">\r\n<label for=\"mce-FNAME\">First Name</label><input type=\"text\" value=\"\" name=\"FNAME\" id=\"mce-FNAME\" />\r\n                            <label for=\"mce-LNAME\">Last Name</label><input type=\"text\" value=\"\" name=\"LNAME\" id=\"mce-LNAME\" />\r\n	                        <label for=\"mce-EMAIL\">Email Address (required)</label><input type=\"text\" value=\"\" name=\"EMAIL\" class=\"required email\" id=\"mce-EMAIL\" />\r\n                            <label for=\"mce-CNAME\">Company Name</label><input type=\"text\" value=\"\" name=\"CNAME\" id=\"mce-CNAME\" />\r\n<label for=\"mce-PHONE\">Phone</label><input type=\"text\" value=\"\" name=\"PHONE\" id=\"mce-PHONE\" />\r\n                        </div>\r\n	                    <div id=\"mce-responses\" class=\"clear\">\r\n		                    <div class=\"response\" id=\"mce-error-response\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\r\n		                    <div class=\"response\" id=\"mce-success-response\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\r\n	                    </div>	\r\n                        <div class=\"clear\">\r\n                            <input type=\"submit\" value=\"Submit\" name=\"subscribe\" id=\"mc-embedded-subscribe\" class=\"button\" />\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </form>\r\n</div>','Beta','','inherit','open','open','','69-revision-8','','','2011-09-23 13:24:20','2011-09-23 17:24:20','',69,'http://localhost:55206/2011/09/23/69-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(85,1,'2011-09-23 12:12:20','2011-09-23 16:12:20','Software companies tout the term ”enterprise grade” as an excuse for their application’s convoluted maze-like interfaces and grey forms designed circa 1990. Supposedly, it offer some unmatched level of stability, security, and scalability. In reality “consumer grade” technologies (such as Gmail) are easier to use, have enjoyed higher reliability, and are hassle free. FoundOPS is committed to “consumer grade” design and in this article I will discuss why your company should be too.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>How did enterprise and consumer design practice diverge?</strong></div>\r\nEnterprise giants software is merely a product of its upbringing. In the past, enterprise software design was steered by large corporate executives who enjoyed the luxury of never using the software they were spec’ing. While consumer marketed companies hired product managers and user experience and interface designers, enterprise companies pushed out features so ugly, only a developer’s mother could love them.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>The new wave of consumer grade design in the enterprise.</strong></div>\r\nBack in July of 2010, Aaron Levie, the CEO of Box.net, a company that produces business content management software for the enterprise, announced in a blog post that “Enterprise Software is Sexy Again”. Levie cited the new wave of enterprise software companies, including his own, PBWorks, Asana, and Workday, which have created software unlike anything the enterprise has seen before. These companies have all experienced great successes, inspiring fear in their multibillion dollar competition. A quick look at the websites, offices, and products of these companies and you’ll see a far greater resemblance to YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook then traditional enterprise companies. With a deeper examination of their product design, you’ll draw the same conclusion I have, that these companies have employed consumer grade design.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>What’s the advantage for my business?</strong></div>\r\nOk, so it looks pretty, but beyond that, well designed software offers a number of advantages to its users.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Significantly shorter training times</strong> – For those with exposure to consumer-grade software like Gmail or Yahoo, learning how to use the next generation enterprise software takes minutes or hours, not days or weeks.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Higher efficiency</strong> – Do more with fewer clicks.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Leverage generation Y</strong> – The latest generation entering the job market has grown up around the Internet. If your old system doesn’t engage and take full advantage of your new hires’ talents, how can your company?</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Visualize your business</strong> - Modern visualization tools can give you live insights on your business.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Be Happier</strong> – Remember the copier scene in office space? (http://movieclips.com/Ndfb-office-space-movie-printer-beat-down/) If you’ve used traditional enterprise software, you can probably relate. You’re going to spend a fair bit of time on your enterprise system. Do you really want to that much time frustrated?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>What is FoundOPS doing?</strong></div>\r\nFoundOPS was developed with a design focus from day 1. \r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>The best interface technologies</strong> -  We use Microsoft Silverlight and HTML5 to create the most immersive user experience possible.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>User-centric design</strong> - Participation from everyone who uses our system (managers, dispatchers, field technicians, your customers) is an integral part of our design process.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Design culture</strong> - We appreciate good design and place value on novel concepts like simplicity and organic interactions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOver the next months, consumer grade design will be permeating into all types of business applications. FoundOPS is strategically positioned to lead this new wave of design and revolutionize how people interact with their business applications. If you are interested in contributing to our design process, please consider joining our beta program at this <a href=\"<?php echo $GLOBALS[\"blogLink\"];?>/beta\" title=\"The Team\">link</a>.','Consumer Grade Design','','inherit','open','open','','41-revision-3','','','2011-09-23 12:12:20','2011-09-23 16:12:20','',41,'http://localhost:55206/2011/09/23/41-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(86,1,'2011-09-23 15:35:24','2011-09-23 19:35:24','Software companies tout the term ”enterprise grade” as an excuse for their application’s convoluted maze-like interfaces and grey forms designed circa 1990. Supposedly, it offer some unmatched level of stability, security, and scalability. In reality “consumer grade” technologies (such as Gmail) are easier to use, have enjoyed higher reliability, and are hassle free. FoundOPS is committed to “consumer grade” design and in this article I will discuss why your company should be too.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>How did enterprise and consumer design practice diverge?</strong></div>\r\nEnterprise giants software is merely a product of its upbringing. In the past, enterprise software design was steered by large corporate executives who enjoyed the luxury of never using the software they were spec’ing. While consumer marketed companies hired product managers and user experience and interface designers, enterprise companies pushed out features so ugly, only a developer’s mother could love them.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>The new wave of consumer grade design in the enterprise.</strong></div>\r\nBack in July of 2010, Aaron Levie, the CEO of Box.net, a company that produces business content management software for the enterprise, announced in a blog post that “Enterprise Software is Sexy Again”. Levie cited the new wave of enterprise software companies, including his own, PBWorks, Asana, and Workday, which have created software unlike anything the enterprise has seen before. These companies have all experienced great successes, inspiring fear in their multibillion dollar competition. A quick look at the websites, offices, and products of these companies and you’ll see a far greater resemblance to YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook then traditional enterprise companies. With a deeper examination of their product design, you’ll draw the same conclusion I have, that these companies have employed consumer grade design.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>What’s the advantage for my business?</strong></div>\r\nOk, so it looks pretty, but beyond that, well designed software offers a number of advantages to its users.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Significantly shorter training times</strong> – For those with exposure to consumer-grade software like Gmail or Yahoo, learning how to use the next generation enterprise software takes minutes or hours, not days or weeks.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Higher efficiency</strong> – Do more with fewer clicks.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Leverage generation Y</strong> – The latest generation entering the job market has grown up around the Internet. If your old system doesn’t engage and take full advantage of your new hires’ talents, how can your company?</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Visualize your business</strong> - Modern visualization tools can give you live insights on your business.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Be Happier</strong> – Remember the copier scene in office space? (http://movieclips.com/Ndfb-office-space-movie-printer-beat-down/) If you’ve used traditional enterprise software, you can probably relate. You’re going to spend a fair bit of time on your enterprise system. Do you really want to that much time frustrated?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>What is FoundOPS doing?</strong></div>\r\nFoundOPS was developed with a design focus from day 1. \r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>The best interface technologies</strong> -  We use Microsoft Silverlight and HTML5 to create the most immersive user experience possible.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>User-centric design</strong> - Participation from everyone who uses our system (managers, dispatchers, field technicians, your customers) is an integral part of our design process.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li><strong>Design culture</strong> - We appreciate good design and place value on novel concepts like simplicity and organic interactions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOver the next months, consumer grade design will be permeating into all types of business applications. FoundOPS is strategically positioned to lead this new wave of design and revolutionize how people interact with their business applications. If you are interested in contributing to our design process, please consider joining our beta program at this <a href=\"<?php echo $GLOBALS[\"blogLink\"];?>/beta\" title=\"The Team\">link</a>.','Consumer Grade Design Extra long title text','','inherit','open','open','','41-revision-4','','','2011-09-23 15:35:24','2011-09-23 19:35:24','',41,'http://localhost:55206/2011/09/23/41-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(87,1,'2011-09-23 15:41:20','2011-09-23 19:41:20','Software companies tout the term ”enterprise grade” as an excuse for their application’s convoluted maze-like interfaces and grey forms designed circa 1990. Supposedly, it offer some unmatched level of stability, security, and scalability. In reality “consumer grade” technologies (such as Gmail) are easier to use, have enjoyed higher reliability, and are hassle free. FoundOPS is committed to “consumer grade” design and in this article I will discuss why your company should be too.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"lightBlue\"><strong>How did enterprise and consumer design practice diverge?</strong></div>\r\nEnterprise giants software is merely a product of its upbringing. In the past, enterprise software design was steered by large corporate executives who enjoyed the luxury of never using the software they were spec’ing. While consumer marketed companies hired product managers and user experience and interface designers, enterprise companies pushed out features so ugly, only a developer’s mother could love t